00:30:30,880 --> 00:30:32,339
That's incredible. Can I keep this?

500
00:30:32,440 --> 00:30:34,169
I'm going to need to keep this. Wow!

501
00:30:40,920 --> 00:30:42,887
How long have you felt robotic?

502
00:30:43,240 --> 00:30:44,401
I don't.

503
00:30:44,640 --> 00:30:48,122
I see, so you believe you're
in touch with your feelings then?

504
00:30:48,240 --> 00:30:50,208
- Yes.
- Both of them?

505
00:30:55,480 --> 00:30:56,810
Apparently...

506
00:30:57,920 --> 00:30:59,125
I...

507
00:31:00,480 --> 00:31:03,211
have trouble expressing myself
in relationships.

508
00:31:04,680 --> 00:31:06,921
- How old are you?
- I just turned 40.

509
00:31:08,039 --> 00:31:10,041
And, how's your sex life?

510
00:31:13,400 --> 00:31:14,619
How's your sex life?

511
00:31:14,720 --> 00:31:18,099
I have sex with people, okay? But...

512
00:31:18,200 --> 00:31:19,929
But you don't connect emotionally?

513
00:31:20,759 --> 00:31:22,204
And what's your biggest fear?

514
00:31:23,720 --> 00:31:25,449
That I'll end up alone.

515
00:31:26,960 --> 00:31:28,290
And gay.

516
00:31:30,079 --> 00:31:31,286
What?

517
00:31:32,519 --> 00:31:34,488
You're 40, you're single.

518
00:31:34,920 --> 00:31:37,684
- "People" sleep with you?
- Are you serious?

519
00:31:38,440 --> 00:31:39,964
- Are you gay?
- No!

520
00:31:49,160 --> 00:31:50,445
Only in bed.

521
00:32:13,960 --> 00:32:15,040
You all right, Grandpa?

522
00:32:15,200 --> 00:32:17,567
Yes, yes, exceptional. Never better.

523
00:32:18,920 --> 00:32:20,000
How did it go?

524
00:32:20,880 --> 00:32:22,803
Exceptional. Never better.

525
00:32:23,400 --> 00:32:24,526
That bad?

526
00:32:24,680 --> 00:32:26,170
Yeah, what the hell am I going to do?

527
00:32:26,839 --> 00:32:28,410
I got to find a job by the new year.

528
00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:30,923
You don't have to find a job
by the new year,

529
00:32:31,039 --> 00:32:32,339
that's an arbitrary deadline.

530
00:32:32,440 --> 00:32:36,885
You can find it January 11th,
March 17th, it makes no difference.

531
00:32:37,200 --> 00:32:38,440
I'll lend you the money.

532
00:32:39,480 --> 00:32:40,685
I don't want to be that guy.

533
00:32:40,799 --> 00:32:43,201
I like that guy, he's a very fine guy.

534
00:32:44,079 --> 00:32:46,082
Well, then, what shall we get Charlotte?

535
00:32:46,599 --> 00:32:48,840
Poinsettias or poinsettias?

536
00:32:49,240 --> 00:32:50,445
How about poinsettias?

537
00:32:51,079 --> 00:32:52,319
Good idea.

538
00:32:53,319 --> 00:32:54,730
I got it, I'll take care of it.

539
00:32:54,920 --> 00:32:56,080
That's all right. No, no, I got it.

540
00:32:56,200 --> 00:32:57,660
- I got it.
- I got it!

541
00:32:57,759 --> 00:32:59,603
I got the god damned flowers!

542
00:33:00,519 --> 00:33:01,700
You get the flowers.

543
00:33:01,799 --> 00:33:03,006
$8.99.

544
00:33:03,400 --> 00:33:04,730
I'll get that back for you.

545
00:33:05,599 --> 00:33:07,807
Hank, you don't have to hide this
from your family.

546
00:33:08,599 --> 00:33:09,964
They're your family.

547
00:33:10,079 --> 00:33:11,969
I don't want to ruin Christmas for Mom.

548
00:33:12,160 --> 00:33:15,209
Well, then tell Angie. She will
understand if the alimony is late.

549
00:33:15,440 --> 00:33:18,807
No, I was a failure at marriage.
I refuse to be a failure at divorce.

550
00:33:18,920 --> 00:33:22,019
You're not a failure. Some marriages
have a shelf life, that's all.

551
00:33:22,119 --> 00:33:23,929
But you and Angie were never happy.

552
00:33:24,039 --> 00:33:26,724
Angie was always looking over
her shoulder for what she didn't have.

553
00:33:27,240 --> 00:33:28,365
FOMO.

554
00:33:29,920 --> 00:33:31,922
- FOMO?
- Fear of missing out.

555
00:33:32,920 --> 00:33:34,380
We fought about it all the time.

556
00:33:34,480 --> 00:33:36,579
Look, I understand. There's history there,

557
00:33:36,680 --> 00:33:38,220
you were high school sweethearts.

558
00:33:38,319 --> 00:33:39,651
No, that...

559
00:33:40,279 --> 00:33:41,326
That's not true.

560
00:33:42,160 --> 00:33:43,888
We were not sweethearts.
That is family fiction.

561
00:33:44,000 --> 00:33:45,569
We were lab partners.

562
00:33:46,319 --> 00:33:48,084
We dissected rats together.

563
00:33:49,160 --> 00:33:51,127
Then, out of nowhere...

564
00:33:51,640 --> 00:33:54,883
band practice at Travis Howard's
house, Angie pounced on me...

565
00:33:55,759 --> 00:33:57,443
while My Sharona was playing.

566
00:33:57,680 --> 00:34:00,619
I got as far as... And then, boom! Done.

567
00:34:00,720 --> 00:34:03,299
I became a dad, same day I failed Biology.

568
00:34:03,400 --> 00:34:06,140
Listen, don't let this one moment
define your entire life.

569
00:34:06,240 --> 00:34:07,980
I'm telling you this from the heart now.

570
00:34:08,079 --> 00:34:10,820
Angie talks while she chews
with her mouth wide open!

571
00:34:10,920 --> 00:34:12,206
It's like a fireman's hose.

572
00:34:12,360 --> 00:34:13,885
It speaks of her character.

573
00:34:14,039 --> 00:34:15,980
She's worse than my Aunt Edna.

574
00:34:16,079 --> 00:34:19,260
Look, Hank, I had kids young,
just like you did.

575
00:34:19,360 --> 00:34:21,965
I had to raise them while I was
still raising myself.

576
00:34:22,079 --> 00:34:25,846
Trust me, this is one small chapter
in your great, big life.

577
00:34:26,119 --> 00:34:27,485
Go out and get some!

578
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:33,728
- Just get some?
- Get some.

579
00:34:37,320 --> 00:34:39,003
It's... The thing is...

580
00:34:39,199 --> 00:34:40,326
Yes?

581
00:34:43,119 --> 00:34:44,485
You've only been with Angie?

582
00:34:44,639 --> 00:34:46,130
Yes, that is the thing.

583
00:34:48,119 --> 00:34:51,168
This is solvable.
This is a solvable problem.

584
00:34:56,840 --> 00:34:59,420
Doesn't it suck how we can
want to run from our families,

585
00:34:59,519 --> 00:35:01,045
but impress them at the same time?

586
00:35:02,320 --> 00:35:03,844
I just disappoint mine.

587
00:35:04,880 --> 00:35:08,125
I think the build up to facing their
disappointment is actually the worst part.

588
00:35:08,239 --> 00:35:10,083
"Anticappointment," I call it.

589
00:35:10,480 --> 00:35:12,686
I can't face the anticappointment.

590
00:35:15,159 --> 00:35:16,400
Is that why you're avoiding them?

591
00:35:17,360 --> 00:35:18,739
I just hate the holidays.

592
00:35:18,840 --> 00:35:20,780
I hate having to reduce
everything I'm doing

593
00:35:20,880 --> 00:35:22,688
down to a sound byte and then defend it.

594
00:35:23,360 --> 00:35:24,599
And I just...

595
00:35:25,639 --> 00:35:28,007
I hate reverting back to how
everyone saw me.

596
00:35:28,760 --> 00:35:30,603
- Maybe you should join the army.
- Yeah.

597
00:35:34,039 --> 00:35:35,166
Are you scared?

598
00:35:36,880 --> 00:35:37,927
No.

599
00:35:41,559 --> 00:35:42,561
Here.

600
00:35:44,960 --> 00:35:46,199
Take that.

601
00:35:46,920 --> 00:35:48,523
How about a little Nina Simone?

602
00:36:54,280 --> 00:36:56,601
Even though he knew he would
never see her again,

603
00:36:57,440 --> 00:37:00,489
Joe would always remember
this amazing moment,

604
00:37:01,039 --> 00:37:03,121
that only happened in his mind.

605
00:37:10,639 --> 00:37:11,800
You know what, Madison?

606
00:37:11,920 --> 00:37:14,539
Guess what, you can really see
the North Pole from up here.

607
00:37:14,639 --> 00:37:16,050
Did you know that?

608
00:37:16,199 --> 00:37:20,807
This is your daddy's favorite place
in the whole wide world!

609
00:37:25,159 --> 00:37:26,420
Three for the red lane, please.

610
00:37:26,519 --> 00:37:28,099
You know, or maybe what we could do is

611
00:37:28,199 --> 00:37:30,340
we could join Aunt Fishy for
a nice cup of hot cocoa.

612
00:37:30,440 --> 00:37:32,659
What a wonderful view.
This was so much fun. Let's go.

613
00:37:32,760 --> 00:37:34,699
Oh, come on. We're not shooting
her out of a cannon.

614
00:37:34,800 --> 00:37:35,860
You used to love those.

615
00:37:35,960 --> 00:37:37,610
Where is your sense of adventure?

616
00:37:37,840 --> 00:37:39,579
- Buried in a good book?
- No!

617
00:37:39,679 --> 00:37:42,081
I am not, you are...
That's just ridiculous!

618
00:37:42,199 --> 00:37:44,088
Come on, Madison.
Let's just go. We're gonna show him.

619
00:37:44,679 --> 00:37:46,603
Nice and easy does it, right, sweetheart?

620
00:38:11,679 --> 00:38:15,320
Every time I go home, I'm told it's so
okay that I am not in a relationship.

621
00:38:15,639 --> 00:38:16,971
It's so okay.

622
00:38:17,719 --> 00:38:18,925
So, how come you're not?

623
00:38:20,000 --> 00:38:21,126
How come you're not?

624
00:38:21,599 --> 00:38:22,840
Who says I'm not?

625
00:38:29,800 --> 00:38:30,847
I'm not.

626
00:38:31,800 --> 00:38:34,201
Yeah, I just wanted to see
your reaction, if you thought I was.

627
00:38:35,039 --> 00:38:36,246
- Okay.
- Are you?

628
00:38:39,159 --> 00:38:41,083
I don't know. Sort of.

629
00:38:42,360 --> 00:38:43,804
He couldn't get away for the holidays.

630
00:38:45,079 --> 00:38:46,206
Prison?

631
00:38:47,280 --> 00:38:48,405
He's with his wife.

632
00:38:53,480 --> 00:38:54,686
Yeah.

633
00:38:56,360 --> 00:38:59,570
Yeah, that's not the kind of thing you'd
want to share with mom and dad, huh?

634
00:38:59,760 --> 00:39:01,125
No, I don't like to brag.

635
00:39:04,760 --> 00:39:06,364
Wait, look.

636
00:39:06,719 --> 00:39:10,284
I don't believe in marriage, okay?
Love fades.

637
00:39:10,679 --> 00:39:11,840
Yeah, so?

638
00:39:12,639 --> 00:39:15,405
Every time a face floods,
that's over a new relationship.

639
00:39:16,079 --> 00:39:17,099
- Right?
- No.

640
00:39:17,199 --> 00:39:19,327
Don't do that. Don't throw me up to me.

641
00:39:19,639 --> 00:39:21,403
Do you even know any
happily married people?

642
00:39:21,519 --> 00:39:22,567
Yeah, my parents.

643
00:39:24,079 --> 00:39:25,570
I mean, you know what I'm worried about,

644
00:39:25,840 --> 00:39:27,460
is that I'm never going to find
what they have.

645
00:39:27,559 --> 00:39:28,925
I'm worried that I will.

646
00:39:29,199 --> 00:39:31,679
The second we left the house,
my parents' marriage imploded.

647
00:39:31,800 --> 00:39:33,289
They fight all the time now.

648
00:39:33,400 --> 00:39:34,606
So do mine.

649
00:39:34,760 --> 00:39:37,001
- You just said they were happy.
- Passionate.

650
00:39:37,360 --> 00:39:38,804
- Ugly.
- Honest.

651
00:39:39,320 --> 00:39:40,367
Heartbreaking.

652
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:45,922
- So, who was he?
- What?

653
00:39:46,400 --> 00:39:48,980
This guy that messed with your head.
I mean it's got to be somebody right?

654
00:39:49,079 --> 00:39:50,969
Otherwise, you wouldn't settle
for a married guy.

655
00:39:51,639 --> 00:39:53,403
You think he's going to leave
his wife for you?

656
00:39:54,199 --> 00:39:56,567
Nope. That was never on the table.

657
00:39:57,320 --> 00:39:59,322
And, besides, we live in different states.

658
00:40:00,320 --> 00:40:01,400
That's good.

659
00:40:01,960 --> 00:40:03,530
Wouldn't want to go
wasting your life, right?

660
00:40:04,320 --> 00:40:06,128
You want to know what's a waste of a life?

661
00:40:06,360 --> 00:40:08,646
A know it all with
a freshly shaved mullet,

662
00:40:08,760 --> 00:40:12,059
who slaps on a uniform and thinks
it gives him the moral high ground.

663
00:40:12,159 --> 00:40:14,766
When, really, he's just risking
his life to please his dad.

664
00:40:26,480 --> 00:40:27,686
Best of luck.

665
00:40:36,440 --> 00:40:37,726
Does your mother know?

666
00:40:39,239 --> 00:40:40,730
She knew before I did.

667
00:40:42,079 --> 00:40:43,161
How do you know?

668
00:40:46,679 --> 00:40:49,001
Listen, if it's hard to talk about,

669
00:40:49,800 --> 00:40:52,086
maybe a little role-play can free you up.

670
00:40:52,199 --> 00:40:54,487
I could play your mom and you be you.

671
00:40:55,519 --> 00:40:56,760
Hi, sweetie!

672
00:41:00,199 --> 00:41:01,610
Hi, Mom.

673
00:41:03,559 --> 00:41:05,561
Stop. You're not doing you right.

674
00:41:05,880 --> 00:41:08,246
- What?
- You're not a robot yet.

675
00:41:08,559 --> 00:41:10,369
You're still a little kid.

676
00:41:11,559 --> 00:41:13,402
I'll be you, you be Mom.

677
00:41:14,320 --> 00:41:17,369
Hi, Mom. It was career day at school.

678
00:41:17,480 --> 00:41:21,099
And Odell said that he wanted to be
a podiatrist like his dad.

679
00:41:21,199 --> 00:41:24,329
And I said, I wanted to be...

680
00:41:24,440 --> 00:41:27,125
Percy, don't gesture so much
when you talk.

681
00:41:28,000 --> 00:41:29,980
Well, Kenisha said that she wanted to...

682
00:41:30,079 --> 00:41:32,003
Percy, stop tilting your head.

683
00:41:32,119 --> 00:41:33,804
Percy, stand with your legs apart.

684
00:41:34,519 --> 00:41:36,123
Percy, don't smile so big.

685
00:41:39,639 --> 00:41:41,403
I said that I wanted to be...

686
00:41:48,000 --> 00:41:49,286
An explorer.

687
00:41:53,199 --> 00:41:56,601
And now you wear a "Do not enter"
sign across your chest.

688
00:41:57,400 --> 00:42:01,166
You couldn't be a gay man, so you
became a stereotype of a man.

689
00:42:01,679 --> 00:42:03,443
Oh, it's so sad.

690
00:42:04,519 --> 00:42:06,300
The things we do in our childhood,

691
00:42:06,400 --> 00:42:09,050
just to fit in, make us stand apart
as adults.

692
00:42:10,960 --> 00:42:14,521
Cold, hard truth is, when I was asked
what I wanted to be when I grew up,

693
00:42:14,920 --> 00:42:16,887
I never said, "alone."

694
00:42:17,440 --> 00:42:19,043
You feel alone with three teenagers?

695
00:42:19,159 --> 00:42:22,539
Oh, them. No. I lied.
I don't have any kids.

696
00:42:22,639 --> 00:42:24,722
- I don't even have a husband.
- What?

697
00:42:25,239 --> 00:42:27,860
Yeah. I knew you'd think, "She's alone,

698
00:42:27,960 --> 00:42:30,610
"she's not getting any younger.
Of course, she'd swallow a brooch."

699
00:42:30,840 --> 00:42:33,059
I opened up to you and you lied to me.

700
00:42:33,159 --> 00:42:35,780
No, I lied before you opened up.

701
00:42:35,880 --> 00:42:37,340
I would never lie to you now.

702
00:42:37,440 --> 00:42:39,806
The conversation part
of this arrest is over.

703
00:42:59,880 --> 00:43:01,005
What?

704
00:43:01,760 --> 00:43:03,603
That scream you made,
coming down the hill.

705
00:43:07,159 --> 00:43:09,083
Is that the Whitehead kid?

706
00:43:09,559 --> 00:43:11,244
The one we used to call Schnozzle?

707
00:43:14,360 --> 00:43:16,487
Quick, quick, what was his name?

708
00:43:16,599 --> 00:43:18,568
- Skippy.
- Don't say, "Skippy."

709
00:43:20,440 --> 00:43:21,771
Oh, here.

710
00:43:22,000 --> 00:43:24,684
Hey. Think you can drop me at the mall?

711
00:43:25,280 --> 00:43:26,519
- Get in.
- All right.

712
00:43:27,039 --> 00:43:28,086
Thanks.

713
00:43:28,280 --> 00:43:30,619
Seriously, what's his name?
I can't remember.

714
00:43:30,719 --> 00:43:31,925
Schnozington.

715
00:43:35,039 --> 00:43:36,326
Get in the back, Rags.

716
00:43:38,440 --> 00:43:40,780
Does your mom know you're out hitchhiking?

717
00:43:40,880 --> 00:43:44,009
No, she took my keys away when
she caught me with pot in the car.

718
00:43:44,920 --> 00:43:46,159
Well...

719
00:43:46,800 --> 00:43:47,925
What?

720
00:43:48,039 --> 00:43:49,530
It's not like we never
got stoned, Charlotte.

721
00:43:49,639 --> 00:43:52,900
- We grew up in the '60s.
- You grew up in the '60s?

722
00:43:53,000 --> 00:43:54,206
Cool!

723
00:43:54,440 --> 00:43:55,940
- Hear that, Charlotte?
- What?

724
00:43:56,039 --> 00:43:57,724
Schnozzle Whitehead thinks we're cool.

725
00:43:59,960 --> 00:44:01,041
Wait. What did you call me?

726
00:44:04,639 --> 00:44:07,099
Yeah we used to... It was groovy.

727
00:44:07,199 --> 00:44:08,724
We knocked around. We went to concerts.

728
00:44:08,840 --> 00:44:10,251
Charlotte met Bob Dylan.

729
00:44:10,360 --> 00:44:12,260
Are you serious? What was he like?

730
00:44:12,360 --> 00:44:14,059
No, I only met him
for a couple of seconds.

731
00:44:14,159 --> 00:44:16,128
Till security dragged you off of him.

732
00:44:16,679 --> 00:44:18,681
- Were you guys hippies?
- Yeah!

733
00:44:18,800 --> 00:44:20,260
- No.
- What do you mean, "No"?

734
00:44:20,360 --> 00:44:22,260
Oh, my God!

735
00:44:22,360 --> 00:44:24,820
She used to speak at rallies,

736
00:44:24,920 --> 00:44:26,967
in front of anybody.
You should have heard her.

737
00:44:27,239 --> 00:44:30,179
No, it's just that I liked
how loud my voice sounded

738
00:44:30,280 --> 00:44:31,780
over the microphone. It's nothing at all.

739
00:44:31,880 --> 00:44:35,248
Oh, no. You were fearless,
man, you had passion.

740
00:44:35,679 --> 00:44:37,807
I don't remember much of that at all.

741
00:44:39,639 --> 00:44:41,449
You don't remember that day?

742
00:44:41,920 --> 00:44:43,045
No.

743
00:44:46,599 --> 00:44:47,681
Really?

744
00:44:51,039 --> 00:44:52,963
That was a long time ago, when...

745
00:44:55,760 --> 00:44:57,125
That was our...

746
00:44:58,960 --> 00:45:00,530
first time, huh?

747
00:45:03,559 --> 00:45:05,449
Your idea to go up in the woods.

748
00:45:07,280 --> 00:45:09,168
That was not. I followed you, I did.

749
00:45:10,079 --> 00:45:11,922
Oh, no I followed you.

750
00:45:12,039 --> 00:45:13,690
I couldn't take my eyes off you.

751
00:45:13,800 --> 00:45:15,085
Yeah, neither could your dog.

752
00:45:16,400 --> 00:45:17,731
Who could blame him?

753
00:45:19,000 --> 00:45:20,889
You can just let me out here.

